He was really patient with me, but eventually I realized he was using a tactic my ex had used as a tool to abuse me. I pointed it out, asked him to stop, and explained why and how it made me feel... but he kept doing it despite me asking multiple times. Eventually he said that it was just how he is.

The easy thing would have been to stay in the relationship and just deal with it...
I had done that with my ex, and I should have seen the red flags sooner for what they were before wasting a decade of my life to unhappiness. I'm proud of myself for being able to draw the line this time.
I will miss him. He is a great guy. But I also need to stand up for me, even if that means speaking up against people I care for.

Your own voice matters too. Especially when it's screaming out inside when things seem to be otherwise fine.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/GPkUown</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Canhealerous]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>This is how democracy dies</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/nrjSL1F</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/rGYGryw.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/eVnSc0u.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This is the one that will end us.

The case, Moore v. Harper, challenges a decision by the North Carolina Supreme Court invalidating the maps of the state’s GOP-dominated General Assembly for egregious partisan gerrymandering. Legislators, led by Rep. Tim Moore (R), argued that their branch of government has the power of conducting “Times, Places and Manner of holding elections” under the U.S. Constitution, a notion commonly known as the independent state legislature theory. The challengers’ case posits that this power trumps that of the courts to decide that their actions violate state constitutions or results in unfair maps.

Essentially, it gives legislators unchecked power over elections, allowing whoever is in power to set the rules forever in their own favor. Which is exactly the point.  

Mallory McMorrow (MI state senator) explains further: 

"Taking up Moore v. Harper gives the U.S. Supreme Court the opportunity to apply a doctrine supported by the Court's new extreme conservative majority called “independent state legislature theory,” or ISLT.

ISLT attempts to vest all control of elections in the hands of only the state legislature, letting them throw out the decisions of state courts, redistricting commissions, Secretaries of State, and even state constitutions. 

If the Court applies this theory, because Republicans control both legislative houses in 30 states, including swing states like here in Michigan, it allows them — and only them — the ability to choose how an election is decided, run, and what districts should look like.

If the Supreme Court enshrines ISLT, it means Trump's Republican Party won't need a coup after the election to install him as President in 2024, they can just change the rules in swing states ahead of time to ensure they get the outcome they want."

